The first virtual service provider will reach the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced and our service providers offer virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - the virtual service provider that forces classical service providers to substantially reduce prices.
Maybe it won't be like this much longer.
We have already written on Mobil.cz that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by ČTÚ, which drew attention to the fact that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in other EU countries.
After the latest European Commission move to regulate roaming charges, this may lead to a controversial situation - text messages sent from abroad to some Czech mobile operators will be cheaper than domestics.
How is it possible that Czech prices are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, the competition that really wants to fight is lacking.
This may sound controversial, since we have three mobile networks and our penetration is over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvořák, President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office, has often agreed with this, who has previously stated a few times that there is no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It may be true that the classic service provider, with its own network, may not have much chance (although it would probably be difficult to find a frequency).
But there is one more option - the virtual service provider.
The entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has brought about a significant price reduction, after which classical service providers also had to react.
Meanwhile, even before big fish such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, voices similar to ours were heard in Britain.
However, it has been demonstrated that such providers have a place and can indeed be successful.
However, for example, we do not have to go too far.
In February this year we informed you about the start of Mobilking virtual service provider in Poland.
In less than half a year, this provider managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest provider there.
In the meantime, Mobilking is backed by the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the possibility of focusing on a much narrower target group.
In order to operate effectively, you need a lot less customers than the traditional service provider.
It does not entail relatively high costs of building, mobile network operation and maintenance.
Virtual service providers in the world thus generally appear as low-cost - offering cheap calls and text messages, which are often offset by fewer services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers text messages at least 50 percent cheaper than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it is a pretty good move to bet on a target group.
This service provider focuses specifically on men.
"Real men choose Mobilking service provider - whom they like, whom they can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company operating this virtual service provider.
It is hard to say whether the idea of Poland can work for us.
Miroslav Čepický, spokesperson for Vodafone, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segment approach on which most virtual service providers are based.
In addition, it has been relatively satisfied with the offer of services."
Not a chance in the Czech Republic, mobile operators claim
However, it seems almost certain that if there is any virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but negotiations in the Czech Republic do not seem very hopeful.
Mobilking will be launched more in other countries of our region," said Jana Studničková, spokesperson for Penta financial group in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
This indirectly demonstrated that existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not very sympathetic to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying their best to avoid any potential competition.
For some time now, the GTS Novera Group has not been hiding its interest in launching the virtual service provider, which is therefore intended to take another step towards making Telefonica O2 a real competitor in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in providing our customers not only wired but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
This option has been discussed again with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in negotiations," says Pavel Kaidl, the group's spokesperson.
Maybe now's a good time.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual service provider will be lucky by the end of the year.
However, his birth is surrounded by an impenetrable wall of silence for the time being.
"At this moment, we do not think that a full virtual service provider should have a place on the Czech market.
Unlike other markets, the Czech market is very special.
So far, we have not been addressed by a single subject offering a complex and serious project in this area," he mentioned to Mobil.cz about the press department of Vlastimil Sršeň, Telefónica 02.
Other operators also refer to the specific situation of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, spokesperson for T-Mobile, exceptionally agreeing with O2, adds: "So far, we have not recorded any viable and bilaterally advantageous business projects on which it could be further based."
And he added, "In the T-Mobile network by the end of the year, it is unlikely that any virtual service provider will show up.
At this moment, we should have a specific agreement on our table so that we can think in such a short term."
Vodafone prefers to turn its attention to meeting its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual service providers, primarily in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is exactly what we consider to be the most rewarding in terms of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is a match to build networks shared for fast mobile internet."
Responsible offices - on the same line with service providers
The procedure of mobile operators is easy to understand, with the entry of another operator leading to an increase in competition, a reduction in prices and a decrease in profits.
So why make it easier for a competition like this to enter?
When something is important to service providers, they are able to cooperate, as well as the huzavona around the birth of U:fon.
ČTÚ was probably under the greatest pressure around the birth of T-Mobile's U:phone.
This is borne out by publicly available information from the ČTÚ website.
But right now, U:fon is a good argument as to why we should not allow the virtual service provider to enter.
Martina Kemrová added: "The environment of the competition in the mobile market was recently influenced by the market access of the fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another player into the market and its services would be subject to high requirements."
However, given this attitude by mobile operators, the total lack of interest of Czech regulators is quite amazing.
In the meantime, it is not just the attitude of ČTÚ, which unfortunately has no right to interfere in economic competition in the Czech Republic, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
Only the Competition Authority is entitled to do so.
But the office has a characteristic attitude towards the whole problem.
"The entry of the virtual service provider into the mobile market would be possible only after the contract between the mobile operator and the virtual service provider was concluded to lease the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not of sufficient interest to traditional service providers," said Kristián Chlapua of the Department of External Relations of the Competition Office.
A statement thus formulated from representatives of service providers would not be likely to surprise anyone.
However, from the office that should represent the interests of consumers and, in addition to others, make sure that no one can abuse their market position, this is more than odd.
Especially if Kristián Chalupa adds, "Outland, where virtual service providers usually operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in the price of mobile phone services."
However, there is probably no pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and on the reduction of prices in the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, it is indeed shocking to see quite touching harmony from the reaction of the three mobile operators.
The question whether it's really just a coincidence is almost self-evident.
As with filling stations, the exact same petrol prices are certainly just the works of chance and tough competition.
"The office has not discovered signs of anti-competitive proceedings in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the service providers has a leading position, i.e. a proportionately greater responsibility for their market activities.
The tools needed to open the mobile market for virtual service providers are probably also missing by the telecommunications regulator," said Chalupa.
The presentation of the market leadership situation is one of many points of debate.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, on the basis of which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, no Czech operator is in a leading position after such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different approach - the creation of a virtual service provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile operator, relatively logically, has a monopoly on its own network.
So it is necessarily dominant in a certain segment.
But even if we did not accept this argument, it would have to be at least a warning to ÚOHS that three mobile operators are acting conspicuously in the same way.
In the meantime, complaints from a range of interested parties (including the already mentioned GTS Novera company) show that they encounter very similar obstacles during negotiations with all service providers.
Transferring responsibility to ČTÚ is a relatively common trick in telecommunications with which the UOHS takes its hands off the whole case.
We've met this before in some of the same situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted telecommunications law, the extension of ČTÚ's powers in the field of economic competition could not be carried through in telecommunications, although many experts hoped to improve the situation.
This is something that the representatives of the U.S.O.S. should know well, but they probably have different interests.
It works when no one's watching.
In the meantime, the operation of some kind of pseudo-virtual service provider, many of which already operate in the Czech mobile networks, remains undetected.
These are companies that publish their own mobile phone service price lists, but which are only partially public.
They're multilevel marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic company client opposite the service provider, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a special customer, you will then receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial terms of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar withdrawals.
"If cases were to arise that you are talking about, it could be a breach of contract terms that we would be dealing with and which could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with that company," replied Martina Kemrová to our question about this problem.
But it is highly unlikely that news of such activity would not reach the responsible people of mobile operators.
In particular, the three companies mentioned may have thousands of customers.
In the meantime, no service provider defends itself against such proceedings.
These companies have not negligible profits from their activities and, unlike real virtual service providers, they are not particularly threatened with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of possible problems: "The law allows similar speculation, however only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They also have to accept that the SIM card is not in their name on their phone, so they cannot have this in full as general customers of mobile operators."
But that's exactly what the ČTÚ should think.
In addition, another question arises for the UOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to a similar procedure, why do they prevent the virtual service provider from being born?
It should be added that the U.S. has a relatively strong power to expose such activity, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the service providers that they did not suspect anything of the kind and that their trading conditions prohibit this.
When we're not the most expensive
As has already been said a few times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has led to a noticeable reduction in the price of services.
In the meantime, in virtually all countries where virtual service providers were established, classical service providers sought to prevent their creation more or less.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small, perhaps too satisfied market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was at these very moments that regulatory bodies intervened, which in no way protected the interests of mobile operators but their customers.
Then, even through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual service provider to be followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are giving each other the whole case.
From our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that unclear competences are useful to them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider is really coming out soon, perhaps the Czech mobile market will resume to move.
If one of the service providers would allow the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it is difficult to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of additional interested parties.
And compared to the rest of Europe, we may no longer be making more expensive calls.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the Best
Listen to four revisions of the new version of the Czech state anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the state anthem Where is my country? on the day of the Czech State.
The anthem was recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the leadership of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solos, choir or instrumental.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka sing.
The authors of the anthem modification are Otakar Jeremiaš and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions on iHNed.cz.
Bělohlavek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful anthems.
He had already told Czech Radio that he deliberately selected young representative voice singers to sing solo variations, which are expressive and popular.
"From the very beginning, both of you and later, I tried to make a clear decision with the orchestra, to take care of the clarity and harmony of the text," he said.
The Czech state anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where Is My Country? was first performed at the Order Theatre in 1834 in Josef Kajetán's Tyl Fidlovačka, complete with music by František Škroup.
It became popular, and people spontaneously considered it their own.
And the first verse of the song became a natural part of the state anthem after the formation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
After the establishment of the independent Czech Republic, it remained one of the seven state symbols.
