Prague transport company delivers chip cards for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 Enter yourself in Prague Transport Company history as the date when the first passenger gets into subways, trams and buses, who will have an electronic coupon in his pocket instead of a paper line ticket.
The coupon is currently available to about 100,000 people who have the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase 30 days and 90 days as well as an annual coupon (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time save their chip cards in the Transport Company's information centers and branches at Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
From yesterday, coupons can be purchased via the website of Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than 400 customers until hours in the afternoon.
Those who start using Internet trading can permanently forget the publishers of metro stations, where they have had to stand regularly for long lines for line tickets.
The coupon can be purchased via the Internet and the Opencard card is saved in one of the thirteen branches of the City Library.
"In these places, passengers have at their disposal a counter with trained servers who help those interested in buying online and also saving their purchased coupons for their cards," said Martin Opatrný, a spokesperson for the project.
In addition to libraries, electronic coupons can be saved to Opencard in self-service vending machines equipped in some lobbys.
What do these vending machines look like?
They are red, they remind us of ticket managers and passengers may have already noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but they should be eighty by the end of the year," added Opatrný.
The coupon is automatically checked instead of the driver
The operation of vending machines starting tomorrow is easy to handle.
Just insert the Opencard chip card and a previously paid coupon is saved from itself.
From tomorrow electronic coupons will apply not only in the capital but also in its vicinity.
So on trains and bus lines around the city from 300 to 499, with which primarily residents of districts in central Bohemia travel to the capital.
"On trains classified as integrated transport in Prague, guides were provided with card readers to determine the zoning validity of coupons as well," explained Philip Drápal of the Ropid organization which compiled the Prague public transport schedule.
In buses around the city, card readers are installed at the driver's desk.
Therefore, when boarding, the driver should not only show the chip card, but also place the Opencard at the location specified on the side of the counter.
This is how the driver checks the validity of the coupons.
"If, for example, the passenger needs to check the validity of coupons, the easiest way to ask the driver to do so," he added Dráp.
Passengers who do not travel by buses around the city and will not remember when their coupon expires can go to the self-service vending machines that save coupons for cards again.
Information on the validity of their documents is displayed here on the display of the device.
The Sudetans wanted a referendum from the U.S.
The Sudeten Germans requested the annexation of Šumava to the United States in 1945.
This is evident from the letter in the collection of the South Bohemian Library of Sciences.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronate of the United States of America.
This is supposed to be the wish that some groups of Sudeten Germans turned to the President of the United States in 1945.
This is also evident from a letter preserved from a private archive, which is now kept in the collection of the South Bohemian Library of Sciences.
Česky Krumlov Germans in the letter ask the U.S. President not to allow the "Sumava County" to be returned to the Czech Republic, which was still occupied by Hitler under the Treaty of Munich.
"The situation has been correctly understood and we really want to be sure of the words that American troops arrive in German territory by no means as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is in the letter, signed with the words "People who bear Šumava's fate in their hearts".
