Rats have feelings, too.
A rat or a moth escapes in the event of danger.
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux is convinced: Animals also have emotions.
But how can they examine whether they feel the same way when they behave like us?
In the Internet magazine "Edge", famous scientists have been publishing their articles for years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE, in one of its series, is looking at the answers to the question "What Do You Think Is Real, Without Proof?"
I believe that animals have emotions and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else being able to prove it. It is true that we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
In this case, however, we can at least hope that the basic configuration of all human brains is the same.
However, as we examine other species and dissect questions of perception or consciousness in general, we arrive in difficult terrain as hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, he does the same thing as many other animals: He pretends to be dead, flees or attacks.
People behave in a similar manner, from which some researchers conclude comparable subjective experiences.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our own subjective experiences to those of animals.
On the one hand, human consciousness-related circuits almost always contain the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and enforcement/control functions).
This wide area is higher in humans than in other primates and appears to be completely absent in other organisms.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, such as knowing who we are or, in the case of planning and decision ability, it is justified to assume that one is even different from other primates.
Another dramatic feature lies in the linguistic nature of man: Because a significant part of human experience is related to language, it is often claimed that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, the animals may be excluded.
However, even if consciousness were not dependent on language, it would certainly be influenced by language, so animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
It is therefore difficult to determine what consciousness can be like for other animals.
If consciousness cannot be measured as an internal and subjective thing, and because of the special hardware it cannot be analyzed based on our own experience, then its research presents us with serious problems.
Most of my discussion concerns the content of conscious living, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that is probably more accessible to science.
The consciousness processes of animals could be examined regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in experiments on short-term memory of primates, especially in the example of visualization.
However, during the assumption also examined by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, they rely more on the neural contexts of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: Both can be the same or not.
Interestingly, this hypothesis also emphasizes the importance of prefrontal cortex in the creation of visualization.
What follows from this regarding emotions?
I'm leading this back to the fact that an emotional system, like that of fear, is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
What we call "fear", therefore, is the mental state in which we are when the activity of the defensive system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) occupies a work memory.
Thus examined, emotions are closely linked to areas of the cerebral cortex that are typical of primates and especially humans.
Complemented with language, perception is divided into subtle degrees, because with words and grammar we are able to distinguish and categorize states to describe them to others alongside ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio is of the opinion that emotions stem from the simpler activities of the cortex and brain stem body perception areas, as is Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much during human evolution, it can easily play a role in the overarching emotions of species.
In theory, I cannot deny that, but I find it unproven.
Pankseep believes that what appears to be fear in rats and humans is likely to also feel so in both cases: How could rats and humans be checked for the same feeling when they behave similarly?
A cockroach escapes in the event of danger, does he also feel fear?
In my opinion, only similar behavior is not yet proof of the same experience.
Although neural fragmentation continues to help: rats and humans have a similar brain stem, but cockroaches do not have brains.
But is the brain stem responsible for the emotions?
And even if this could be proven for humans: how can we prove this in the case of rats?
I think rats and other mammals, but even cockroaches, who knows, have feelings.
However, I do not know how to prove this.
And since their emotions are suspected to be fundamentally different from ours (as human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I research the emotional behavior of rats rather than emotional emotions.
In any case, progress in this area is expected at the neural level if we measure the same in rats and humans.
Just as I don't research language and consciousness in rats, I don't research emotion, because I don't know if they exist.
This may seem like a short-sighted approach to someone else, but I'd rather go ahead than keep bumping into a wall.
I'm a practical emotionalist.
