Dark matter affects the flight of space probes
A mysterious phenomenon has been causing uncertainty among researchers for years. Dark matter affects the speed of space probes during the so-called swing-by maneuver.
Experts fear that Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity cannot be entirely correct.
The space probe "Ulysses" flew into space for nearly 18 years.
Due to soon-frozen fuel lines, it is threatened with freezing death.
For years, scientists have been confused by a mysterious phenomenon called swing-by anomaly.
Swing-by is the gravitational swinging pit of space probes, during which they gain additional momentum in the gravitational space of a celestial body, such as the Earth.
So the probes can save a large amount of fuel.
The European-American Cassini-Huygens research probe, like the Ulysses Sun probe, also used this physical trick.
However, what amazes researchers for years has been: Flying objects do not behave fully as they might be expected under the ancient law of gravity.
Instead, abnormalities occur in speed.
Probes unexpectedly accelerate or slow down.
So far, physicists have found no explanation for this effect.
The phenomenon was dubbed swing-by anomaly.
Some experts fear that even Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity may not be entirely correct, which perceives the mass attraction of matter as a curvature of space.
American physicist Stephen Adler, of the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, continues to firmly believe that Einstein was not wrong and is trying to explain the swing-by anomaly with the so-called dark matter discovered by astronauts in the universe.
"The dark matter may be responsible for the anomaly, which may even be found all the way near Earth," says Adler.
The existence of dark matter was only known to space scientists ten years ago.
Obviously, it exerts a gravitational force that can be seen to have an effect on other celestial bodies.
However, the material itself is completely invisible, i.e. it does not emit or repel any electromagnetic radiation, especially visible light.
Scientists calculate that a good one-fifth of the entire mass of the universe consists of dark matter.
