Prices have dropped by over $20 a barrel since last Monday.
Over the past two weeks, commodity exchanges have been shaken by the Wall Street financial turmoil, and some powerful hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After prices reached $145.29 per barrel in July, they dropped to almost $90 per barrel at the beginning of this month before falling again under the influence of immeasurable uncertainty on financial markets.
On Monday, anxiety again overwhelmed investors even after Congress leaders announced that they had reached an agreement over the weekend regarding the economic rescue operation, which is the largest in history.
The news was clouded by concerns that the financial crisis would not be over for a long time.
As the latest event of the unfolding crisis, Citigroup will acquire Wachovia Corporation's banking business, announced Monday by the government.
Meanwhile, the Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments have partially nationalized the European financial conglomerate Fortis.
According to Barclays Capital analysts, as a result of desperate weekend talks "it seems that the rescue operation failed to revive the stock market trading mood."
As the economic situation deteriorates, it is expected that the demand for goods, such as oil, will also be reduced.
"The future of the market for ordinary shares, interest rates and currency rates has become uncertain worldwide," wrote an analyst from Deutsche Bank to investors.
"We believe that the market for goods will not be avoided by the 'outbreak'".
The biggest issue for the commodity exchange is the extent to which the "disease" of the U.S. is infecting the whole world, especially with regard to China."
As oil consumption decreased due to the slowdown in economic growth, bank analysts cut off their expectations for next year, reducing their oil and gas price forecasts for 2009.
With the feat of the second quarter, the team set their record
After spending more time in the Jets jersey than anyone else in the past more than eight seasons, Shaun Ellis, who played in defensive end position, thought he had seen everything.
But then he watched the second quarter unfold on Sunday, when the Jets turned a scoreless game into a sensational game.
"I've never seen anything like it," Ellis said.
The second quarter began after the sloth game of Jets and Arizona Cardinals came into full alignment with the dark clouds towering in the sky.
Brett Favre, quarterback, gave Laveranues Coles a 12-yard touchdown pass, a perfect forerunner for an afternoon during which their evolving collaborations significantly improved.
Favre gave Coles two more touchdown passes in this quarter, including when two cornerbacks in a row fell 10 seconds before the half ended.
"I wasn't sorry for the trouble," Favre said about all of his passes to Coles.
"Pokoli is a good player.
We've been able to communicate well with each other, no matter what people think."
While Favre and Coles were playing ball, the defense stopped Cardinals quarterback Kurt Warner.
Darrelle Revis, who played in cornerback position, caught a bad pitch and threw it back 32 yards, which was a touchdown.
Eric Smith, safety player, reached into another pass and scored the ball.
David Bowens, linebacker, managed to knock the ball out of Warner's hand.
This last turn could have been the most amazing move in the match.
However, when the Cardinals lost the ball 10 seconds before the end, and the Jets scored, Jay Feely kicked a 20-yard field goal, setting the 34–0 result.
This was the best result the Jets have ever achieved within a quarter.
When the Jets coach Eric Mangini was asked to describe the mind-blowing nature of the game, he said, "The second or third quarter?"
When he was told that both - in the third quarter, the Cardinals scored 21 points without the Jets scoring any - Mangini said, "I have to tell you that I enjoyed the second quarter much more than the third.
We scored a lot of points in a short time."
Rested Gebrselassie breaks his own world record
Ethiopian Haile Gebrselassie once again showed why many consider him the best mid- and long-distance runner ever to have lived when he broke his own world record in Berlin on Sunday, making him the first to run the 42.2 kilometers in 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With a win on a comfortably flat course in 2:03:59 time, Gebrselassie improved 27 seconds on his 2:04:26 previous result, which he achieved in Berlin last year.
By the age of 35, Gebrselassie set the 26th world record of his career in so many areas that he won a World Championship in almost all terms from 1500 metres to the marathon, or a world record.
Last month, Gebrselassie missed the Beijing Olympic marathon, fearing - which in retrospect may have proved excessive caution - that air pollution would further exacerbate his asthmatic problems.
Instead, he entered the Berlin marathon.
In almost perfect conditions - in sunny weather, initially at 9 °C and in the end at 13 °C - Gebrselassie won on Sunday, at an incredible speed of 2 minutes and 56 seconds per kilometre.
Since runners not previously running on the marathon, such as Gebrselassie, and Paul Tergat of Kenya turned to longer distances, the marathon record has declined by more than two minutes in the last decade since Brazilian Ronaldo da Costa won in Berlin with a 2:06:05 result in 1998.
After the win on Sunday, Gebrselassie told reporters that two weeks ago his two legs had cramped and could not train for two weeks.
It is obvious that during the forced rest, he refreshed himself and did not rust.
"I'm so happy," Gebrselassie told reporters.
"Everything worked out perfectly.
I started training again a week ago, and today I had doubts, but in the end everything was fine."
He received some reviews - especially from Kenya, Ethiopia's East African rival - that he uses too many aids during his competitions, usually avoiding many world-famous marathon runners, relying on his pace runners as running on track, and placing world records before the competitive spirit.
However, this criticism hardly reduces Gebrselassie's greatness in long-distance running.
Gebrselassie reached the halfway point at 1:02:04 with four Kenyan pace runners on Sunday.
Two top Kenyan runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, gave the rhythm to Gebrselassie after the pace runners were exhausted.
Shortly over 4.8 kilometers ahead of the target, Gebrselassie passed Kwambai with a final sprint, who finished second with 2:05:36, improving his personal best by 5 minutes.
Kamathi came in third at 2:07:48.
In the women's race, Irina Mikitenko, born in Kazakhstan, who is now a German citizen, finished a notable year with her seventh fastest win of 2:19:19.
The world record is held by the British Paula Radcliffe with a time of 2:15:25.
Last spring, 36-year-old Mikitenko won a surprise at the London marathon with a 2:24:14 result.
He was unable to attend the Beijing Olympics due to his alleged back injury, however he quickly healed and won the Berlin marathon, where he improved his individual peak by five minutes. It was the third marathon long-distance run he attended.
He won the race with a clever calculation: he first allowed a group of four Ethiopians and Kenyans to advance and gain significant leadership and then came after them after running about 30 km.
Ethiopian Askale Tafa Magarsa finished second with a time of 2:21.31 while Kenyan Helena Kiprop came third with a result of 2:25:01.
A separate city, the pride and ordeal of black people
In the experience park in Greater Orlando - a few miles away from everything that shines, loud and powerful - a quiet small town hides where the pride and complications of African-American life experience have been born.
Eatonville, the first purely black town to integrate into the country and which was Zora Neale Hurston's childhood home, is now not as simple as she described in 1935: "the five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown leather, 300 good swimmers, lots of guajavas and two schools, without prison."
It's a place of pilgrimage now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have already attended the annual Zora Festival. The Eatonville celebration series is held in honor of Harlem Renaissance's most famous female writer Hurston.
Yet, in many ways, the city he described and made a tourist attraction - which is also included in the Florida guidebook published by the Project of Federal Writers of the Crisis Age - is distinct from his surroundings.
Just as independent, dignified and shut-in as it was in the 1930s, when according to a writing by Hurston, Florida, urban blacks often refused to share their real thoughts with white people who "know so little about us that they don't know what they're missing."
Even in the year when black presidential candidate Barack Obama encourages an open exchange of views on the race issue, many here are distrustful of outsiders' glances.
"We are very careful how our story is told," reported 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here all his life and is a member of the oldest church in the city.
"You have to tell it right."
Eatonville has long been characterized by a paradox of victory and struggle.
At the same time, it is a historic model of black standing, while at the same time it is a community of almost 2,400 people where poverty indicators reach double the national average.
It is partly a literary node, and partly an example of a sometimes looked down, sometimes praised, southern, urban, black culture that flourishes in the shadow of oak trees.
It is not surprising, then, that the residents here are both proud and defensive.
And the image of Eatonville has been important since Zora, (everyone here calls Hurston).
In books written in the sincere, strong dialect - like "Mules and Men" (1935) and "They Eyes Were Watching God" (1937) - he introduced his hometown to the world.
Five sections of the Florida guidebook have transformed the city, which lies next to Route 17, which leads from the long forgotten center of Florida to one of the sites of black history and human drama.
Hurston, who was brave in both life and literature, like drum roll, introduced his readers to Eatonville's first mayor Joe Clarke's business and then looked into the more confidential spheres.
He wrote: "To the right of the road we find the modern public school, with a white trim on a brown background, carefully maintained courtyards and playgrounds that Howard Miller tends, although he can barely read and write."
He mentioned the widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn was "selling all kinds of drinks and anything that might be needed in temporary accommodations."
Thus, in a few hundred words Hurston associated Eatonville with autonomy, but also with illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
It is clear that the Fodor's guidebook presented it differently.
This description really didn't appeal to everyone.
"Zora told the things as they were," reported 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls. Hurston made them immortal by quoting the slippery songs that men sang about their beauty.
He added, "Some people didn't like that."
Hurston is still remembered here as the lively eccentric who often visited home after his family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, aged 77, recalled that when Hurston stormed into the city, he usually arrived unannounced in a rumbling Chevrolet, smoking, and long trousers to a city where people are still proud of their dignified dress.
Most people were enchanted, Franklin said, but many were foresaid.
"People were always happy to see Zora," Franklin said.
However, on the terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, he added swinging in his chair, "He never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor and his books were no longer reissued.
It seemed to have been forgotten by Eatonville along with most of the world.
Although he was once a popular writer, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, he was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where he had previously lived.
There were no significant commemorations or large, public readings in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood how much he enriched the world or what he left us at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of the book Hurston biography published in 2003, "In the Rainbow".
The turning point came in 1980.
Orange County officials wanted to build a five-lane road through the city instead of the two-lane main street, Kennedy Avenue, which played an important role in the community's life.
The expanding Orlando has already penetrated the western border of the city by Interstate 4 highway connecting the states.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering after a difficult historical period.
Among other things, forced integration ended the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, fighting over racial blending gave the community a taste of hatred.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys came over and threw oranges and other things at people on the side of the road," Franklin said.
"There was a lady who died of this.
They threw a watermelon out of a car."
In a letter to "The Orlando Sentinel" in 1955, Hurston questioned the decision of the Supreme Court requiring violent integration. He said of the resolution "Brown v. Board of Education": "it offends me more than respects my race."
Today residents say that although the desegregation of schools was positive in some respects, it weakened the unity of the Eatonville people and undermined the confidence of young people.
"The black children are accustomed to being hugged - I remember this - man hugged his teacher both in the morning and in the evening" reported N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins, executive director of the nonprofit organization "Let's Guard the Community of Meg Eatonville".
"This lasted until students and teachers came from a common place," he added.
"We didn't hug our white teacher because he was a white teacher - I mean there were cultural differences between us," Nathiri said.
However, human rights helped the rise of many other Zora Neale Hurston - black writers, actors and artists who rose above prejudices, as she did, with such optimistic self-confidence and lines as: "How can anyone deprive himself of the enjoyment of my company!
This is incomprehensible to me."
In 1975, Alice Walker wandered off to Hurston's unmarked grave and began struggling to return her reputation.
Five years later, a recognized Hurston biography written by Robert E. Hemenway was placed on the shelves of bookstores, which brought him back to being one of America's role models.
The road construction project would have started just as Eatonville's most famous daughter was re-focused on attention.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw him as a savior.
The community began organizing a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the county would ruin with its main road.
Thousands of fans arrived for the opening event two years later, and many have since returned to the ceremony every January.
Several years later, the county abandoned its road construction proposal.
"Because of five lanes on the main road, the community has revived, turned to full speed, which means true civic pride," said Nathiri.
Boyd put it simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the road construction project helped to change the city's image of itself.
There was an increasing number of people living outside the city, such as lawyer Rachelle Munson, who began attending church here in 1993, and the locals began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the national historical list in 1998.
The new single-storey library (named naturally after Hurston) was opened in 2006, on re-enveloped and beautified Kennedy Avenue.
Eatonville remained Florida's cuckoo egg: it's not quite ten km from the center of Orlando only, but sometimes one feels like a suburban side street during summer rain; it's as small as when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today 90% of residents are black.)
They still welcome with caution the outsiders who arrive here in search of Eatonville's story, what he has to say.
Most interviews require prior permission, and some things - such as Eatonville's oldest fresco, painted by a white man and depicting blacks working in the fields - should not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, including the confident teacher Jones, who is particularly attracted to bright red, fear that their distinct community is misunderstood.
And yet, as the Hurston Festival grew wider, the pride of the hometown grew.
In particular, youths increasingly view Eatonville as Hurston saw his own race: wonderful, along with his problems and everything, neither better nor worse, as proud, creative, industrious, foolish, and confused as other racial and ethnic groups in America.
An honest civic attachment is heard from the words of Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return after graduating from college to take a job with the local government or the police, which he believes are in need of help.
And it seems the younger ones have also learned to characterize Eatonville correctly, such as the 11-year-old Winter Park twins Alondra and Alexia Kenon.
"Most people who just travel through here think this town is nothing compared to the others," said Alondra Kenon recently after worship on a Sunday.
"But if someone stops and takes some time to get to know their history, it's a very nice city."
We all speak the language of finance here in New York.
