The couriers still rattle their metal tea trucks through the sidewalks, carrying trays filled with muffins for morning meetings.
There are still Spanish-speaking men shuffling among the blockhouses, carrying as human mules fifty or so ironed shirts hanging on a yoke-like loop across their shoulders.
Office workers are still waiting in line for their breakfast sweet pastries at food trucks on the sidewalk, and it is still impossible to catch a taxi between 4 and 7 p.m. on weekdays.
