Meanwhile, Austria is conducting a conscience inquiry following yesterday's parliamentary elections, during which the language of the political balance is tilted to the right.
The two far-right parties, which won almost 30% of the vote, campaigned for the Future of the Freedom Party and the Alliance Austria, a highly anti-immigration law, and some of their slogans were branded xenophobic by their critics.
Heinz-Christian Strache, President of the Freedom Party, who has won more than 18% of the vote, has also expressed his disapproval of the campaign against headscarfs and burkas, as well as of foods alleged to be associated with Islam.
At the party's final Grand Assembly in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood", which helps prevent the strengthening of Islam.
Both parties want to ban the construction of mosques and minarets arguing that they are political symbols of the ongoing Islamicization of Austria and Europe.
According to polls and analyses conducted immediately after the elections that brought about the victory of the far-right, the change was due to the largely young voting base who are concerned about their future in the European Union.
