"I'm not taking photos on stage because I want to introduce the artist from a personal side" Photographer Günther Bauer
No set, no ruffles, no dancing shoes.
The great masters of flamenco from near the body, without the excitement of performing: to get to know the ordinary faces of dancers.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the ordinary man.
And these two sides cannot be separated, except in intimate moments away from the audience, when we can watch a personal move, grasp the depth of a caught look, or marvel at the beauty of the idle but expressive hand of the artist who is not about to perform on stage.
In the German photo series Flamenco-people, Günther Bauer combines the theatricality of singers, dancers and guitarists with this less-known ordinary side of masters.
Through the photos, the flamenco presents its specific iconography from different angles.
The exhibition, which is part of the month of Flamenco Photography, "reflects the increasing international importance of flamenco day by day," the creator believes, adding that Flamenco-people "could be anyone, as the observer realizes that these images do not depict artists in a typical way.
These people on the street are artists who can bring passion, sadness, joy to the stage... and enslave the audience.
At the same time, stage photography is not suitable for capturing their personality.
Their personality and character reside in the depths of their being.
I wanted to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to use the camera to capture the personality of the greats of flamenco."
With momentum from the Cante de las Minas festival, Bauer embarked on his long journey in 1997, during which he made portraits of flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers with a disc camera.
These portraits quote classical photography thanks to the camera and the choice of subject.
However, the application of various stylistic tools breaks with traditional visual representation and suggests modernity. The following thought faithfully reflects Bauer's idea of flamenco: "This is a music with traditional roots, but it changes from day to day and is always fascinating."
It's not the dance, it's not the singing or the music itself, it's the artist's personality and character that charms the audience.
In recent days, the leading motif of works that can be seen in the El Photomata gallery is the search for an encounter with its essence, the artistic sewing, which becomes visible through the way of perception, existence and visualization.
Known figures of flamenco, including Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Moreente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, are hallmarked by the names of this photo collection featuring nearly sixty artists.
The project also became a flamenco anthology, about which an album covering portraits presented at the exhibition will soon be released.
Bauer's passion for portraits spurred him to repeat the idea two years ago with the series "Portraits of Veteran athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concept of Flamenco-people differs slightly from this, the photographer adds: "I really like taking pictures of people, getting to know them and entering their lives for a longer or shorter moment.
In my opinion, the most difficult genre of photography is portrait.
You meet people, you meet people, you meet people you don't even know sometimes, or you just take a few minutes to shoot.
But despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to realize my ideas.
A selection of contemporary flamenco portraits, titled Flamenco-people, can be seen at the El Photomata Gallery, located at the calle de la Mata 20 parallel to Alameda de Hércules until October 16.
