Repeated drunk drivers will be ordered to install "Alcolock"
After three drunk driving violations, the Ministry of the Interior would require the driver to install a device that would prevent the vehicle from starting if the driver was in a state of drunkenness or did not blow into the structure.
The proposal was presented in June and is now being dealt with by the State Prosecutor's Office, according to which the pilot project will last for a year.
Since the aim of the project is to re-enter the market, the driver will also have to attend a repeat course on transport education.
In addition to the Attorney General for Transport Safety, the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Auto Safety Technology Foundation (FITSA) are also involved in the experiment.
According to statistics, 30–75% of motorists arrested several times due to drunk driving are back in the car.
This would be prevented by Alcolock, as the system connected to the vehicle determines the alcohol level of the air sprayed in it. If it is greater than allowed, or if the driver has not blown into the device at all, the system will not allow the car to start.
The cost of the instrument of more than EUR 1000 would be borne by the infringer.
A relevant study in the US in 2007 demonstrated that vehicles equipped with such instruments could reduce the number of infringements by up to 65% in the first year after installation.
In Spain, it is estimated that this rule could save 115 people each year.
The measure focuses on offences for two reasons: on the one hand, it is easier to prevent them from turning into criminal offences,
on the other hand, it is easier to introduce as the legal reform is being implemented in the usual way, while the necessary reform in criminal matters would require an amendment of the basic law.
The instrument is not yet available in any commercial form on the Spanish market, although it has already been installed in some industrial and public service vehicles in experimental mode.
The House of Representatives will vote tomorrow on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party which, on a French model, calls for the system to be installed in school buses.
