Who speak in their sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean those who wake up and fully alertly describe what happened to them that day, but those who talk while they sleep.
The phenomenon may seem scary at first, but it's actually completely harmless.
This benign sleep disorder is called somniloquismus.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
I'm sure more of you have been told that you spoke at night.
Regarding its frequency, it may be completely rhapsodic (for example, it occurs only once in a high fever illness), or more regular (every day, weekly or once a month), and usually the next day the child does not remember anything.
Its appearance cannot be traced back to a single underlying cause.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders such as nightmares, nocturnal uproars, nighttime bed wetting (enuresis nocturna) or sleepwalking, but it is not legal either.
As already mentioned, it may be a condition with a high fever, or even an accompanying phenomenon of stress or increased excitement.
In any case, it's been poorly studied so far.
The intensity of speech is also very variable.
It may be quiet, calm, may consist of incoherent words, murmuring, but unlike all of these, it may also take the form of shouting, crying, or longer speaking.
If the phenomenon is very intense, it is recommended to observe the child and contact the specialist. The study may reveal whether there is a problem that causes a great deal of anxiety and can therefore provide a solution.
As mentioned above, this is a benign phenomenon and consequently there is no cure unless it is accompanied by another treatable form of sleep disorder (e.g. insomnia or stress).
But there are some things we can do, and here's a bunch of preventive measures:
Make sure that the child remains calm before going to bed.
Choose comforting games and avoid children watching fear - inspiring or more aggressive TV shows or series.
For children who tend to be nervous or have difficulty relaxing, we teach them some relaxation methods to find inner peace more easily.
This will help the child to sleep more calmly.
If you do start talking while you're sleeping, let's try to keep calm.
Remember, it's harmless to the child, and they won't remember anything the next day.
Useful advice
Don't wake the child.
It would be unnecessary, because the child is unconscious, but he'd be out of sleep.
Even though he talks, he actually continues to sleep and rest.
Remember, if you are often accompanied by intense anxiety, it is advisable to consult a specialist or to explore what causes the child to become very anxious.
If you speak plainly (this is a rarer case), do not start asking questions to learn anything from him.
It wouldn't be necessary, because he's not conscious enough to collect his thoughts while he's asleep.
On the other hand, you can only hear the speech, but you do not see the dream images associated with it, so be careful with the interpretation of what you have heard and with possible conclusions.
Don't ever tell the kid they can question him about his secrets at night.
Not even for fun.
