Blood is safe again
The Héma-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation yesterday. President Dr. Francine Décary had good reason to celebrate because Héma-Québec has now become one of the safest and most effective blood-giving societies in the world.
Most importantly, he managed to regain people's trust, which was severely shaken by the 1980s and 1990s scandal about infected blood.
As is known, the national blood reserve treated by the Red Cross blood supply service in Canada was infected with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and general upheaval, the Government of Canada launched a formal investigation in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to make suggestions to avoid similar cases in the future.
While Judge Krever delayed submitting his report, some provinces set up their own committee to design a new blood management system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee served this task.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two blood supply services were established in Canada: one by Héma-Québec serving Quebec, and the other by all other provinces and the Canadian Blood Supply Society responsible for supplying the two territories.
"When Héma-Québec began its activities in 1998, barely 38% of people had confidence in Quebec's blood supply system," Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was desperate.
"In the coming years, however, we managed to regain the trust of people as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in the area." Décary proudly states that almost 94% of the Quebec population already considered Héma-Québec to be reliable in early 2008.
However, Dr. Décary does not forget that "trust is an extremely fragile thing".
Since the foundation of Héma-Québec on 28 September 1998, it has applied the precautionary principle.
During this period, a number of cases of mad cow disease, the new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were discovered in Europe, says the doctor, who has been in charge of the company since its founding in 1998.
"We had no idea if this disease was spreading through blood.
Therefore, we have relied on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports. According to this, if we are uncertain and there is a risk of developing a serious disease, we must apply exclusion measures. In this case, it was the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which causes brain changes, thus inevitably leading to death.
Therefore, in April 1999, we did not accept blood from persons who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
And a few years ago, no doubt, it was found that the disease spreads through blood.
This incident convinced us that it made sense to apply the principle of caution."
In 1999, a technique was released on the market that allows for a much more sensitive diagnosis of HIV virus. This nucleic acid test (NAT), which can directly detect the virus itself in the blood of blood donors, rather than antibodies to the virus on which previously used tests were built.
The NAT test allowed us to shorten the window period, which will keep us from getting infected until we can detect the virus in the blood using our technical tools, explains the expert.
This period could be reduced for a period of less than one week.
Thus, they significantly reduced the risk that blood donors could unknowingly infect blood and that this could not be detected.
These improvements greatly reduced the risk of spreading AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, the risk of receiving HIV-infected blood is 12 million to one.
"In other words, this means that we should distribute 12 million blood products while someone is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it would take more than 24 years for such a case to occur and someone to become infected with HIV via a blood product.
I think that today anyone can accept or prescribe blood transfusions in order to restore health, says the number one leader of Héma-Québec.
"The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We never know what new pathogen will enter the system.
After all, it was only last year that the chikungunya virus was released on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, enters the blood with insect bites.
Therefore, we must be constantly on guard," Dr. Décary continued, and then stressed that besides emergency reserves, Héma-Québec must provide sufficient permanent reserve.
"As the population ages, demand is also increasing.
Since anticancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor population, as the number of people in the network who are eligible for blood donation accounts for only 3% of the Quebec population.
However, every healthy person aged at least 18 years who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of applicants do not accept blood because they are infected with AIDS or malaria and those who have visited a country where malaria kills are not entitled to donate blood for a year.
"With this 3 percent we have enough reserves to meet the needs of hospitals.
It's very rare to run out of supplies.
However, we need to increase the number of blood donors to the extent that the existing ones are getting older, because they can't give blood after a while.
However, it is very difficult to convince people to donate blood, but it is even harder to keep them and get them to become regular blood donors.
In this rushing world today, you barely have one hour to go and give blood," Sorry Francine Décary.
Hema-Québec, a farmer of the 297 million dollar annual budget, provides not only blood products but also human tissues, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeball tissues, and skin tissue, which is used almost exclusively for severely burned persons.
These tissues are analyzed, modified, and frozen, and then placed at Héma-Québec, which also manages Quebec's only public stem cell bank.
Once treated as medical waste, blood can be obtained from umbilical cords that are rich in stem cells, thus allowing for the treatment of severe diseases such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago that the thousandth cord blood sample entered our bank, and we plan to take over a thousand new samples each year.
At the beginning of next year, we are probably starting to offer these for organ transplants," said Dr. Décary, who said that the cord blood removal program is very popular nowadays.
"Many mothers are sad that they don't have the opportunity to do so" - that is indeed true, as Héma-Québec is not in a position to make this complex and costly program available in every hospital in Quebec.
