Opinion - Orwell oratory of Barrick Gold
A letter from Patrick J. Garver, deputy president and CEO of the Barrick Gold mine in Canada, was published in the September 17 issue of Le Devoir.
Following Orwelli's discussion, Garver states that the world's largest gold-producing company has filed a $6 million libel suit against three authors and a small-money publishing company in order to initiate a so-called "public debate".
Although the judges are independent and impartial, their decision is made, especially in defamation trials, not by truth, but by law.
Not surprisingly, Garver was deeply silent about this fundamental difference.
Would it really be the best way for Barrick Gold to argue in public to destroy anyone whose position is contrary to his?
Regardless of the outcome of the lawsuit, the authors and publishers of the book Noir Canada must spend significant sums of money on defense and struggle in an unequal fight where on the other side there is an army of lawyers supported by almost inexhaustible sources of the mining industry.
Otherwise, in such an unequal struggle, the tactic is often used to destroy the defendant and reach a friendly agreement that not only silences the opposite, but even intimidates those who would try to re-emerge the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, he should have expressed his views to the public.
Although in many other countries where Barrick Gold operates, this is done differently, in Canada, contentious parties generally do not strike each other with sticks but express their thoughts.
The mine would therefore have been enough to open its books and dossiers and prepare for a real debate in a press, media, publications, paying for independent research groups that could have shed light on the issue.
But it seems that Barrick Gold does not trust the public and sweeps aside petitions and letters written in defense of the authors of Noir Canada in one move.
Perhaps you could explain to Mr Garver how you can initiate a "public" debate if, at the same time, you ignore this public opinion?
In the Deputy President's mind, this word probably means only lawyers who have been paid handsomely, rather than the total population of Canada: the meaning of the concept is thus greatly narrowed down.
Even those derogatory to others in a democratic state deserve freedom of speech.
However, what Barrick Gold does not understand - or do not want to understand - is that Noir Canada's authors and publishers are mainly supported by the public because it condemns the rough procedure of the mine.
The public is ready to listen to Barrick and make a judgment, but this would be done on the basis of civilized arguments, rather than by a lawsuit for silence for many. (In relation to the term "public debate", Barrick Gold recently called on Noir Canada authors in writing to refrain from using this term.)
