Wall Street rescue mission - Democrats and Republicans agreed
Republican and Democratic leaders of the Bush administration and Congress finally reached an agreement yesterday on the economic rescue operation, which is the largest such plan since the Great Depression in the 1930s.
A plan worth US$700 billion, aimed at curbing the financial crisis that has raged on Wall Street for months, still needs to be approved by the two houses of Congress.
Key points of the plan are: more effective monitoring of implementation by Members; new mechanisms to ensure repayment of planned state funds; new provisions to keep the number of houses seized due to non-payments; right of access to the salaries of the managers of assisted companies.
U.S. Finance Minister Henry Paulson, Nancy Pelosi, President of the U.S. House of Representatives and Judd Gregg, Republican MP in the trial, announced the good news yesterday, a few minutes before midnight, after the two-day marathon trial ended.
"We have made great progress towards a solution that will work effectively in the markets," stated Henry Paulson, representative of the Bush administration.
"We have done everything to save the real economy and American citizens from the current crisis that has hit Wall Street," the Democrat MP explained.
"The most important aspect is that if we don't do this, then shock, chaos and confusion will be huge in the daily lives of Americans," Republican Representative Judd Gregg said.
The trial was accelerated in the last few hours fearing another failure would have a detrimental effect on the mood of investors.
The agreement was granted until the opening of the stock exchange this morning.
The two presidential candidates who joined the negotiations late showed willingness to reach an agreement, but they did not welcome the fact that the situation had escalated to the end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama credited himself with expanding the agreement with elements such as provisions relating to the preservation of house ownership or the payment of executives of companies assisted by the state.
"When we ask taxpayers to take certain extraordinary steps because of other people's irresponsibility, it is not very welcome.
But these steps are necessary," he noted on an American television show.
And when his opponent, John McCain, was asked by another network if he would vote for the proposed plan, he replied: "I would like to know the details, but I hope I do."
"What I have read in broad lines is already visible from what we all need to digest and by which we can move on.
The opportunity to do nothing is simply unacceptable," he said.
According to the $700 billion plan, taxpayers' money would be used to buy the dubious demands of American financial institutions, some risky, unsellable assets.
The plan was preceded by a 14-month crisis initiated by the bursting of real estate balloons. This first led to the collapse of risky real estate loans (secondary mortgages), then spread to other debt (trade) securities, and eventually caused the freeze of liquid funds and the upheaval of banks and financial institutions.
The first draft agreement was overthrown by a group of Republican representatives last week.
It seems that we have managed to get out of this dead end since the Democrats agreed to provide certain "toxic" devices for companies in difficulty rather than being acquired by the government.
In order for all members of Congress to be satisfied, the plan also included a provision requiring that if the government has to bear losses under the program for five years, it may impose new taxes to recover its resources.
As part of the new plan, a $250 billion installment would first be paid; a further $100 billion may be followed if the president considers it necessary.
The payment of the remaining $350 billion should be approved by Congress by another vote.
In return for the help, Washington acquires a stake in the supported companies, whereby he receives dividends from the profits and can sell it after the crisis has gone down.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the seizure of real estate to cover the mortgage loans covered by the plan and to set the maximum wage and severance payments that can be paid to the managers of the companies affected by the crisis.
The drafters would like the plan to be voted on by the House of Representatives today and by the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite their efforts, however, it is still not certain that the plan will be approved.
Yesterday, statements opposing the plan were repeated among both Republicans and Democrats.
"It is absolutely clear that Washington does not hear your voice," stated Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's Finance Committee.
"Yes, we have serious financial problems.
Yes, there are solutions.
But there is no one that would benefit taxpayers."
Brad Sherman, a Democratic representative leading a small congressional grouping called the "sceptic faction", presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred excellent economic experts, including three Nobel laureates scientists, wrote to us to ask Congress not to rush and to examine carefully which path it chooses," Sherman stated yesterday.
In Europe, once again, it was understood that this was a global crisis.
Following a crisis meeting, the three Benelux states announced that they would nationalise part of the Fortis banking group worth EUR 11.2 billion (16.3 billion US dollars).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French BNP Paribas announced that it would not buy up its rival on the verge of bankruptcy after losing €2 million (US$2.9 billion) as a result of the crisis in secondary mortgage loans in the United States.
Fortis with 85,000 employees is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurance companies.
"It's not thrown out money," Dutch finance minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
"We gain voting rights and influence in the bank.
This is exactly the kind of thing that depositors and households appreciate now that the situation promises to be uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the English Manche, the British government seems to be about to nationalize another bank that has been swept away by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over the total of Bradford and Bringley bank's ongoing loans, of which real estate loans amount to £41 billion (US$75.5 billion).
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that they would acquire the subsidiaries and customer stock of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would thus be the second bank after Northern Rock to be nationalized by the British government since the start of the crisis.
