The psychology of overbiding: why are we releasing more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overvalue goods.
The neurological-economic foundations of this known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been uncovered by neurologists and economists at the University of New York.
According to a study published in Science magazine, people do not want to be left behind in a type of competition such as eBay’s auction, so they pay too high a price.
The research tried to map the nervous system scheme of this "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers lotteryd, and the other group participated in a player auction while examining the active brain areas of experimental individuals using the functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) method.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction game - in which overbiding the other party is an essential element - the striatum, sub-brain cortex complex was activated intensely upon the loss of the game.
This brain area plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system among several other functions.
Therefore, researchers believe that the upheaval of the price can be explained by avoiding the intense reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theory, the members of the research group economist also conducted a financial follow-up investigation.
In this, three groups bid against one partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the real value of the product concerned and they made their bets.
In addition, another group was promised that if they were out of the game in a win, they would be rewarded with $15 in cash.
The third group, on the other hand, had just received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a losing auction, the group members also lost this money.
The difference between the two groups, therefore, was merely that for one of them, they emphasized winning, and for another, losing.
However, proving the hypothesis of neurologists, members of the team playing "against loss" were willing to bet higher than the control and "winner" groups.
"These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
To date, they have only explained the events of the auction with the joy of winning and avoiding risks.
Only neurological imaging methods helped resolve the contradiction between these two theories by now coming to a third explanation," stated Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when should we consult a doctor?
Around half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death in Hungary.
The number of people infected with hepatitis at home is 100,000, but only 7,000 are treated, which is why patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is a common name for infections of the liver caused by different viruses.
Their symptoms have many similarities, characteristic of hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ.
Hepatitis viruses are transmitted in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E via the gastrointestinal tract (e.g. contaminated food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (sudder, vaginal discharge, saliva).
Travelers should definitely be vaccinated against A and B viruses, and there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after eating the infected food, generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal complaints and nausea.
Thereafter, jaundice on the skin and whites of the eyes develops, stools become light, urine becomes dark, healing may take two to three weeks.
A million people die worldwide from more serious types of disease, hepatitis B liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only 1 in 10 infected patients receive medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected people don't even know about their disease because the pathogen insidiously destroys their liver cells, in many cases they don't show their first symptoms until 20 to 30 years later.
Thus, it is very important that early prevention and regular screening tests are carried out.
There are far more than average cases in three groups: between people undergoing blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
There are currently 200 million chronic hepatitis C infections in the world.
Since the disease may already be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to contact the GP if any symptoms of unknown origin are detected.
Recognizing the disease in time can be cured, the virus can be eradicated from the body, thus eliminating infection and preventing cancer from developing.
September 30 is the World Day for Hepatitis, first held in 2004 by organisations representing patients around the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God hurt less?
According to a recent study, religious faith acts as a painkiller that could have facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment, examining how belief in God affects people's sense of pain, reported by the British Telegraph.
In the framework of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were electroshocked while all were studying a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to rule out much of the pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was also revealed that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for controlling pain.
The inquiry is the first in a series of research in which, in addition to academics, scientists, philosophers, and theologians participate from various parts of the university.
The investigation took place precisely by attaching a sparking device to the left hand of the experimental subject, which provided the electroshock.
Researchers asked those involved in the experiment to look strongly at two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and Leonardo da Vinci's picture of Lady with Hermelin painted in the 15th century.
The investigators hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would cause a kind of religious state among believers, while the da Vinci image was chosen because it was not too different from the other and was thought to be soothing.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner machine, during which time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive parts while either looking at the religious-themed or general image.
Catholics reported that while seeing Virgin Mary, they felt "safe" like they were "careful" and "rested, filled with peace".
While watching the religious picture, 12 percent less pain was reported than when they saw Leonardo’s creation before them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself participated in the study, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any powerful image, including atheists, only the right photo should be found.
"We should find a picture for whom they feel very positive, like a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases changes our personality," Wright added.
After the great results, the only question is, if Leonardo or a painter of similar caliber showed a picture of a madonna to the believers, what effect would that have on their pain control?
Would the sight of a quality Virgin Mary mean even better results?
