The flying of the bumblebee is imitated by the intelligent car
What would be the best way to develop technologies to prevent collisions, if not to imitate barrier sensors in the natural world?
Like bees.
In the surprising project presented at the CEATEC in Japan, the bumblebees gave the Nissan engineers the strategic idea of how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built the BR23C type bioimitation car robot control system, a robotized minicar that was endowed with the properties of the bees, with the ultimate goal of facilitating the development of a system that eliminates all collisions.
During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is in fact very similar to our safety shell, explained Kazuhhiro Doi, brand director of technology PR and research and development at the exhibition.
It is important to have a complex eye of the uterus, which can be seen at an angle of more than 300 degrees in each direction.
To copy the function of the complex eye, engineers touched the idea of laser telemetry.
This identifies obstacles in a 180-degree field of vision before BR23C within a 2 metre range, calculates their distance, and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately transforms into an action to avoid collision.
The obstacle is detected in a fraction of a second, and then the car robot, mimicking the movements of the uterus, immediately changes direction by turning its wheels to the extent necessary to avoid collision.
In any other way than the current system, this avoidance maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive manner.
"If this were not the case, the car robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, leader of the Mobility Laboratory and car-robot project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety barrier, a layer within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
However, in a way other than bees, the deviation must not be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it must be only two-dimensional, and only towards the rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the endless possibility for bees to avoid other bees, only rotating movement and acceleration and slowing were used here as an option available to the car robot.
BR23C employs lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer life span than that of the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, the instinctive intelligent reaction is the important, not the ability to process and store data even less.
This device only has to process and respond to a few input signals per second.
There is no need to preserve them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, thus constantly using only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
There's no need for gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in developing immediate bypass technology, which Nissan estimates can enter mass-produced cars within ten years.
An additional application option may be the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to lead the driver to the specified end goal by avoiding obstacles on the road.
