The compromise on the package was supported by both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain.
Commenting on the outcome of the compromise, Finance Minister Henry Paulson stated that the programme will work and be effective, but that further work is needed. Pelosi says this is not about saving Wall Street, but turning the wagon around the economy.
The written version of the package was made public before the opening of the Asian markets on Sunday evening 8 p.m. (i.e. Monday morning, Central European time), but did not cause a spectacular run-up in the fairs.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will vote for the first time on the draft legislation under the name of the Economic Emergency Stabilization Act of 2008, which takes place on the programme, and then it will be on the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke with Pelosi on Saturday night and was then welcomed to the White House for news of the settlement.
We are pleased with the progress made at night and appreciate the efforts of the two parties to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy, said Tony Fratto, a White House spokesperson.
The program is otherwise different from the Bush administration's original proposal, which would have meant that the $700 billion would have been spent one-in-one on the purchase of poor quality, credit-backed securities.
Now, in the first round, a maximum of half of the $700 billion can be spent using 250 billion immediately after Congress is expected to vote on the matter on Monday, from which the Treasury buys loans-backed, poorly rated securities, and the fate of an additional $100 billion depends on the President's decision.
The programme will be monitored by a separate body, which will also be involved with the President of the Federal Reserve.
Spending the other half of the 700 billion depends on another decision by Congress.
Under the law, the Ministry of Finance can use a combined tactic: it can simultaneously purchase bad loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities, as well as other types of "toxic" loans.
The purchase can take place in the framework of auctions and directly - the Ministry's competent authorities told us.
The legislation allows the companies concerned to participate in an insurance scheme where the financial portfolio guarantees the assets of concern for which companies will pay a fee corresponding to the expected damage.
Henry Paulson said that the law provides the necessary means to reach up to $700 billion for the urgent needs of the American financial system, whether it is a widespread purchase of bad assets, or insurance, or the avoidance of systemic risk associated with the collapse of a large financial institution.
We will take the necessary steps to be ready to introduce the law as soon as it is signed, he added.
However, the bosses of banks in distress and in need of state aid can expect to limit their exit money, which the overseas slang simply calls a golden parachute, to be limited by the government.
Payments are limited only in certain cases and the limits depend on how the Ministry of Finance assists.
The restriction essentially means that if the ministry buys under auction, an extra tax will be levied on the gold parachute unless the devolved bank manager is retired.
When bad loans are purchased directly, the government will aggressively intervene to ensure that executive money is not exaggerated.
The image includes that existing gold parachute contracts do not change, the restriction only applies to new ones to encourage participation in the program.
This is the first time in American history that there will be a statutory restriction on the remuneration of CEOs, commented on the measure by the chairman of the House of Representatives' Committee on Financial Services, Democratic Party Barney Frank.
In addition, in the banks participating in the programme, the State acquires the right to acquire a stake, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, as they can ultimately win the deal as soon as the economy and the bank that has been rescued recovers.
The draft law states that over the next five years, the President must submit to Congress a proposal providing for how to return the expected losses to taxpayers from the financial sector.
On both sides, of course, there were those who expressed doubts about the plan.
This is not what American citizens have asked us to do, i.e. it does not protect taxpayers' dollars, said Republican Representative Darrell Issa of California.
