Industrial prices continued to increase
Domestic sales prices of the industry increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 compared to the previous month and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, reports the KSH.
Industrial export sales prices were 1.1 per cent higher than in July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to a year earlier.
As a result of the domestic and export price changes, industrial producer prices were 0.7 percent higher than the previous month and 3.2 percent higher than the previous year.
Domestic sales prices of the industry increased only to a minimum by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sector also increased slightly by 0.1 percent compared to July.
The largest price increase occurred in August 2008 in the leather product and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 percent), mainly due to the 4.6 percent increase in the production of bags and straps and the 2.5 percent increase in the monthly price of footwear production.
The higher price levels of plastic and chemical raw materials have resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and product manufacturing sector (1.6 percent).
Price reductions occurred in the sectors of oil processing (1.4 percent), electrical machinery, instrument production (0.9 percent), and, to a minimum, wood processing (0.1 percent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
In the other manufacturing sectors, we measured a price increase between 0.2 percent and 0.9 percent.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector, which is significant in the domestic sales of the industry, increased by 0.3% in August, mainly due to the protracted impact of the official gas price increase from 1 July.
Twelve months' comparison, in terms of domestic sales of manufacturing industries, saw the largest increase in prices in the oil processing sector (32.4 percent).
In the manufacturing of metal processing products, an 11 percent increase in prices was observed in the food, beverage and tobacco sectors with a decisive weight of 13.2%.
Price reduction occurred in the textiles, textile goods production (2.5 percent) and electrical machinery and instrument production (0.3 percent) sectors.
In the other manufacturing sectors, price increases ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
Prices have increased by 10.2 percent in the manufacturing industry as a whole over the last year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector were 18.7 percent higher than those in the previous year.
Domestic sales showed the largest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) in August in the capital goods manufacturing sectors of the target groups of the sectors.
In the consumer goods manufacturing sectors, prices have increased by 0.3 percent and in the energy and downstream sectors have not changed compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, the largest price increase compared to the same month of the previous year was observed in energy and downstream production sectors (16.8 per cent).
We measured a 6.8 percent increase in prices in consumer goods manufacturing sectors and a 1.4 percent decrease in prices in capital goods.
Export sales prices of the industry in HUF increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, and decreased by 3.9 percent in 12 months compared.
In a month, our domestic currency weakened by 1.7 percent compared to the euro and 7.1 percent compared to the dollar, with 7.5 percent compared to the euro compared to August 2007, and 15.9 percent compared to the dollar.
