The European Equal Opportunities Summit began today in Paris, hosted by France, representing the Presidency-in-Office of the European Union.
Lívia Járóka, the Fidesz representative of the European People's Party, drew attention to educational segregation in her message to the plenum as one of the main speakers of the professional deliberations, because this is one of the most serious violations affecting Roma children and this is also the most serious obstacle to their effectiveness.
The high-level conference, on behalf of the French Presidency, was opened by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
The representatives of governments, the European social partners and the most important European rights defenders and civil society organisations in the field of equal opportunities were invited to attend the deliberations.
Járóka, according to the press office of the Fidesz EP Group, warned that, in addition to discrimination on recruitment, Roma are primarily excluded from the labour market due to their low education.
"The vast majority of Roma youth have no secondary education, and as a result of poor quality primary education, only an insignificant proportion of them can obtain higher education".
Járóka also stressed that, as a fundamental human right, education has a key role to play in the enforcement of other human rights.
Investing in early education for Roma children can mean strengthening the economy of European Union Member States.
According to the Member, it is necessary to raise this awareness to the widest extent, including among Roma and non-Roma.
Because as soon as the Roma student starts school, their chances of becoming productive members of the labour market increase; they contribute to the national budget through taxes on income and consumption.
"The Roma must have their right to quality education under the right of their citizenship of the European Union and guarantee the elimination of their low-quality and separate education," said Lívia Járóka.
According to the congresswoman, it is essential to bring together the European Union in an effort and action-oriented way to speed up the desegregation processes at school, and proper enforcement of existing and planned anti-discrimination guidelines is essential.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation, unemployment, give Roma children the opportunity to contribute to Europe's future as full citizens", Járóka demanded.
The aim of the European Equal Opportunities Summit, held annually since last year's meeting in Berlin, is to provide a unique forum for promoting the objectives of equal opportunities and non-discrimination at European and Member State level.
