Accidents at Work: Napolitano says prevention is more important than anything
Every day in Italy, there are 2,500 accidents at work, out of which 3 end in death and 27 end in permanent disability.
According to occupational accident insurance records, nearly 1,200 deaths occurred in the workplace in 2007.
The numbers show the seriousness of a phenomenon that is still one of the most common causes of death today and is causing almost twice as many casualties as manslaughter.
Today, for the 58th time in all counties of Italy, Anmil is hosting the day of victims of accidents at work traditionally held on Sunday, October 2, to raise awareness of this dramatic problem by institutions, social organisations and mass communication.
"The worrying data reported by Anmil, as well as the tragic events of recent days, confirm that prevention plays an extremely important role in accidents at work," said President Giorgio Napolitano of the Republic in his message to Pietro Mercandelli, President of the National Association for Accidental Disability at Work.
The head of state sincerely praised the "confederation's persistent commitment to prevention at work, to protecting the interests of workers who have suffered accidents, to helping family members of victims and to raising public awareness".
"T tragedies of this nature and shared honestly by all, attracting media and public interest by their size, are a source of outrage, but in reality we have to face dramatic, repeated cases every day".
Napolitano openly admits: "we are undoubtedly in a shortage of resources, funding education and information is crucial.
In-school initiatives aimed at providing direct information to young people on the threshold of entry into the world of work are of particular importance.
We have a duty to maintain interest in the phenomenon, not to let it become less noticeable about the social importance of the issue, and we need more effective legislation that needs to be enforced.
The President of the House of Commons Gianfranco Fini, for his part, stressed "how serious accidents at work ending in death are of social importance to all of us, and the institutions are required to put an end to this as soon as possible".
"Data on accidents at work shows a slight improvement, but the number of deaths of this type is still incredibly high," commented Pietro Mercandelli, president of Anmil.
"We do not want this downward trend, however, to be coupled with decreasing attention, because the greatest tragedies occur just when attention is slowed down."
"We believe that at a general level we are still not doing everything we can to combat this phenomenon, which could be solved through a complex action programme.
In our opinion, we need more stringent supervision and control - stressed Mercandelli - as well as a more marked intervention in the field of labour training, starting from school education."
"There is also a need for further efforts to inform and make public opinion aware," he added.
However, what is most needed is a more responsible employers' environment against a phenomenon that poses a social problem".
Afterwards, Mercandelli criticised "the gradual deterioration of the compensation safety net for victims of accidents at work" and the "aid trend towards which the system has been drifting in recent years".
"The goal, therefore, is to return to workers the safety afforded by insurance, because the fate of those suffering an accident cannot depend on the arbitrary actions of the legislators, or on the handout measures".
MP3 players can cause hearing damage
Listening to portable recording devices for longer periods of time and at high volume, such as MP3 devices, can cause permanent hearing loss -
In its report published in Brussels, the European Commission, the Scientific Committee on New and Newly Identified Health Risks (SCENIHR), has published today’s opinion.
"The expert opinion shows that 5-10 percent of those who listen to their portable music player for more than one hour per day for five years with a high volume can suffer permanent hearing loss," says the explanation.
"It is worrying that young people who use high volume portable music players and mobile phones in bulk and often are unaware that they can irreversibly damage their hearing," said Meglena Kuneva.
"Scientific surveys indicate an undisputed risk that we urgently need to respond to," added the EU Commissioner.
The most important task is to inform consumers and disseminate information about this.
In the light of this opinion, we also need to review existing control systems so that they can function and keep pace with the latest technologies".
Brussels asked the independent scientific committee to look at the problem in view of the prevalence of portable music players and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise pollution caused by them.
"Researchers confirm that we have cause for concern and the European Commission, in cooperation with Member States and stakeholders, is ready to look at possible measures to protect children and minors exposed to noise pollution caused by portable players and similar devices," said a member of the Committee.
The current European safety requirement sets the maximum noise level that can be emitted by portable music players at 100 dB, but is nevertheless accompanied by growing concern about hearing loss data due to excessive use of such sound sources.
At the same time, there are solutions such as reducing the level and duration of noise pollution, which can significantly reduce these hearing damage.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee explains that for mobile players who listen to music at a high volume (over 89 decibels) for five hours per week, noise pollution exceeds the current maximum noise limit for the workplace.
If a person listens to music in similar circumstances for a longer period of time, there is a risk of permanent hearing loss after five years.
This affects about 5-10 percent of those using portable devices, which can mean 2.5-10 million people in the EU.
Rome, Alemanno sets up a committee responsible for the future of the capital
It starts today, it lasts until March, the results are expected in June.
This is the timetable set by the Metropolitan Municipality for the operation of the committee "The future of the seat capital of Rome", which met this morning at its new headquarters behind the baths of Caracalla.
Over the next six months, President Antonio Marzano and the other 49 members of the committee will draw up Rome's guidelines.
Following the conclusion in March, the study and plans will be evaluated in the General Assembly and municipal committee so that the Metropolitan strategic plan officially approved by the Municipality and Mayor Gianni Alemanno can be submitted in June.
"This is an entirely independent committee, in which all political, social and cultural ideas are represented - and Alemmanno stresses - it is in his task to come up with proposals for the development ideas of Rome on which policy makers, the Assembly and the Local Government Committee, can rely.
There is no conflict of jurisdiction, we just wanted a platform where great plans could be made for the benefit of Rome.
In March, after he has completed his work, the committee will be dissolved because he has a fixed term of office.
In June, we will present a strategic plan based on the work of the Committee on the Future of Rome, the mayor said.
For those who consider the Commission's operation unnecessary, on the grounds that the advice it has put forward is not binding, Alemanno replies: "It all depends on what work the Commission will do and on the quality of proposals it will put on the table.
If the quality is satisfactory, as is the case with the Attali Committee in France, which I take for granted in the case of Rome, its contribution will play an important role.
The power of politics is often fragmented in dealing with daily affairs and in dealing with urgent cases that arise from time to time.
On the other hand, we, taking into account perspectives, look further and plan for a longer term and are committed to working for the development and future of Rome".
The mayor of Rome wishes to state that "this Commission cannot be regarded as a useless "waterhead", as it is absolutely free, will not cost any euro to the citizens of Rome, but on the other hand it serves as a thought incentive and aims to involve the finest minds in the capital".
According to Alemanno, "there is a need for an open-ended and flexible strategic framework that allows our city to jump to the standard it needs so much, thinking in a united spirit about its future".
About the future on which the mayor of Rome emphasises: "it will not only be limited to the current municipal framework, but it will look much further", not only will we see the future metropolis and the status of the capital, but also "the role it can and must play as the capital of Rome, Europe and the Mediterranean".
