The Elite Is in Danger
The phenomenon was felt a few days ago when the House of Representatives did not vote for the $700 billion bailout package presented by the White House: much of the Americans were more interested and still interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is supported by yesterday's New York Times, which informs us that due to the current crisis, there has been a break within the Republican Party, which is increasingly divisive between a traditional, subdued attitude to the east coast supporting federal institutions and business circles and a growing anti-D.C. and financial world stance in the central and southern states.
This line was critically manifested during the House vote mentioned in the introduction.
However, the above event is just one of the major changes that the economic reshuffle that is still taking place predicts or permits to be seen, and not only in the United States, but in the entire Western world, perhaps even outside.
It seems that the crisis, both in the US and in Europe, is only speeding up the long-standing underlying phenomena that are solidifying in this new atmosphere and finally coming to light.
The first such phenomenon is re-updating, bringing back to the public a dual category of state sovereignty, in connection with a kind of re-nationalisation of the economy.
The crisis is affecting banking and financial institutions which, although they have a close relationship with the rest of the world, are primarily, and quite widely, bringing people and families with them that live in a single country, in a single state.
This, on the other hand, is a direct political problem for those on the government: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people who are also electorate.
So the crisis seems to be global in economic terms, but in political terms it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be essentially stranded outside the coastline: the European Union is a fine proof of this, which, by lavishing between different interests and different national strategies, cannot set a single policy stance.
Thus, everyone expects intervention from individual national governments, the rescue package, the recovery and the new rules, but most importantly the opening of funds: as only individual states have economic resources, a financial set that may be able to make things right.
They also have the means and the authority to use them: under certain circumstances they have two invaluable resources that no other market and no international organisation will likely ever have to this extent.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed by the crisis on national statehood is fully in line with the fact that recent economic growth attaches increasing importance to a factor closely related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had already entered the abstract world of increasingly sophisticated technology, and we were convinced that the global financial world was destined to rule the world, we suddenly had to realize that our future was increasingly dependent on things that were less and less abstract than water, crops and oil.
Things that can be transported from one side of the planet to another, yet are wholly linked to a demarcated location, an area.
Thus, whoever rules the area has much more trump cards than, unfortunately, was born in a place where there is no crop, no oil, and no water.
I would like to move on to the second novelty, which suggests a kind of fault line.
Anyone who says it's territory, state, government necessarily says it's politics, in other words leadership.
From this point of view, the economic crisis seems to be producing two contiguous phenomena:
On the one hand, the objective recognition of the need for credible leadership, someone who can handle events.
On the other hand, current management, especially economic leaders, brings a complete loss of credit, who have proved to be completely inadequate and have proved that many are still in dim territory before them.
Together, the two are of even deeper importance and, in a sense, more disturbing: a sense of credit loss, impatience, inadequacy, and separation that affects the entire leadership elite in more and more Western countries.
So it seems that the belief that the time of the social elite at its peak has expired is spreading among a wider population. It expired before their actions, experiences, lifestyles, culture, in the complex sense of the word, were taken into their own. This makes the social elite increasingly alienated from the opinion of the majority.
In other words, the need for leadership, in a veiled form, is fueling a diverse but strong delegitimation movement against the ruling class and the traditional political system. This is manifested in unanticipated "rebellions" by voters, or in recent times in sudden changes in public sentiment. For example, the rise of Conservatives to power in Austria and Bavaria, the collapse of the Labour Unit in Britain, or the revolt of U.S. Congressmen against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the Italian right).
It seems that the traditional elite, along with its parties, programs, and even its famous intellectuals, understands less and less, and therefore is less and less able to represent what has been happening for some time in the deeper sections of Western society. Furthermore, the economic crisis is getting stronger, spreading and potentially able to generate increasingly inordinate emotions.
Despite all this, talking about "the imminent rebellion of the masses" would be an exaggeration, to be honest.
But keeping your eyes open isn't bad at all.
We can walk with super powerful glue on the wall
By using a super-powerful glue to defeat gravity and walk on the wall like Spider-Man.
This is the goal set out by several American research centres, and a group of four institutions are close to finding a solution.
With a piece of glue of just 2.5 square centimetres, researchers managed to glue a 100-pound body to a vertical wall and hold it there.
THE American journal STUDY - A Science published the discoveries of some researchers at the University of Dayton, Akron, Georgia Institute of Technology, and Air Force Research Laboratory.
