Researchers drew the idea from the foot covered with gecko microscopic folds, which provides perfect grip for the animal.
Tests with various materials such as glass, Teflon, and abrasive paper have confirmed that the new glue is ten times more effective than the soles of those reptiles, but at the same time "it is easily detached from the wall", Liming Dai, a researcher at the engineering faculty of the University of Dayton, explains.
FALON TO GO? - "This material may be useful as temporary glue," Liming Dai adds.
Can we walk on the wall, just like Spider-Man? Maybe, but researchers think about a less impressive use than connecting electronic devices, because carbon nanotubes are good at driving heat and electricity.
You can also find additional applications in the field of space exploration.
Superheroes can wait.
