Don't use juice.
Care should be taken with grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These high vitamin-containing drinks, especially popular in the summer, when added with certain life-saving medicines, alter their absorption, increasing or reducing their effects, as appropriate. This may also have serious health consequences.
David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, drew attention to the risks of co-administration of canned or fresh fruit juices and certain medicines. The professor announced at the 236th national meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia: a glass of grapefruit, orange or apple juice can reduce the absorption of certain life-saving medicines, thereby preventing their beneficial effects and endangering the patient’s health.
Grapefruit juice had already been placed on the defendants' bench when it was discovered that it was able to increase the effects of some antibiotics, antihistamines, anti-anxiety, heart rhythm control, and neuropharmaceuticals to levels considered toxic.
RISK MEDICINAL PRODUCTS - Two years ago, the Italian Institute of Pharmacy itself published the news in its official bulletin and warned doctors and patients to take seriously the risks associated with this co-administration and to pay attention to what they drink when taking medicines such as Diazepam or Methadon.
GRAPEFRUIT alone - According to researchers, orange and apple juice also contain substances that inhibit the effectiveness of medicines.
A long list of active substances whose absorption is hindered by grapefruit and other fruit juices could be listed.
This is what Michele Carruba, professor of pharmaceuticals at Milan State University, draws attention to: "This kind of discovery is usually immediately signalled to the various national and international pharmaceutical institutions, who, if necessary, ensure that the information contained in the prospectus of the given product is changed.
This is why you should always read the instructions for the medicine you intend to take, and if something is not understood, do not let yourself be influenced, but ask your doctor or pharmacist clearly," emphasized Ansa.
