Open Office, third edition worth the "anti-Microsoft" package
Today, the OpenOffice.org 3.0-personal productivity-enhancing open program code application package is released, targeting ever wider layers as a free alternative to Microsoft Office, from home to office users, from freelancers to public administration.
After almost a year of work supervised by SUN Microsystem and carried out by volunteer developers, the new Open Office comes to the public with several new features: in addition to the welcome screen and the rethought, less Spartan user interface, it offers several essential innovations, such as compatibility with Apple Mac OS X operational systems, and also supports the new ISO standard ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format.
Special attention has been paid to compatibility with Office 2007 so that Open Office can also open Microsoft documents with new extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
Interesting is the specific function of a few modules, such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations. This can be useful for sending files by email. Another feature supports importing PDF files into a graphics module by retaining the page location layout.
On the same interface, you can create "hybrid PDF" documents that combine the typical Adobe format with spreadsheet or text editor elements.
Sharing within applications has also been through a number of improvements: the spreadsheet manager supports the common use of workbooks, but prevents overwriting each other's works. Each employee's comment is marked in a different color, which helps easier recognizability during the inspection phase.
Some companies are already working to make some of OpenOffice's features available from the Internet (on the cloud, on the cloud), so the final version is likely to be presented in the coming weeks.
The Italian version can be downloaded from the following address after it has been posted on the mirror pages to English since Friday: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html
The program package is also available for Linux in addition to the usual Windows and Mac OS operational systems.
On request, we can take the installation CD at home or at work.
Freeness is probably the biggest attraction for the spread of home application, but the Open Office program package is now trying to kick the ball in the business sector as it can count on a number of administrative and school projects.
There is no lack of educational, advisory and service services ideal for small and medium-sized enterprises, which can open up new business perspectives.
The Open Office consists of five basic modules: Writer, text editor for Word; Calc, spreadsheet manager for replacing Excel; Impress, Powerpoint presentations; Dbase is the best known, similar to Access database manager; and finally Draw is the graphics module.
The goal of 2008 is to achieve 5 million downloads. However, considering that with the release of the new version we are already at 3.600,000, this figure will probably be higher than expected.
