Good-bye, old Cinema Paradiso, the days of old cinema halls are over in the cities
Traditional cinemas close for Multiplexes.
"A city where there are no cinemas, blind town, is like a face without eyes".
The pictures taken by director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively show what is happening in Italian cities, but also in rural regions.
The displacement of cinemas - the emergence of large multi-room cinemas in the suburbs, and as a result the withering of single-rooms in city centres - seems inevitable and irreversible, but at the same time bears all the features of a true cultural crime.
When historical and memorable places disappear, "it's like a friend of ours is leaving, a familiar with whom we shared our journey and many experiences," says director of Cinema Paradiso. The film, which twenty years ago marked the Oscar Award and the Grand Prix of the Cannes Festival to Tornatore, tells the lyrical history of a small town cinema, the yearning, after a cinema experience that may have been lost forever.
The data provided by Anec, the largest association of operators, is clear: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed. The biggest losses have been recorded by cinemas in large cities: 10 cinemas closed in Florence, 9 Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 Turin, and 5 Palermo.
Emilia-Romagna is at the forefront of the most affected regions, which lost 82 single-room cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And the fact that the expansion of multiplexes is the only evidence of their disappearance is that Italy has the highest number of newly opened multi-room cinemas in these three regions: in the last five years the number of halls has increased by 195 in Lombardy, 81 in Tuscany and the same amount in Emilia-Romagna.
"The number of units in Italy has increased irrationally," says Anec President Paolo Protti. "It's okay to build new facilities, but the survival of those already in existence should also be ensured, because when a city cinema closes, not every passer-by is willing to cross over into multiplexes.
Not to mention the unpaid financial funds to support operators: the state's overdue debt is around EUR 10 million.
It is both ethically and morally shameful that the government does not comply with the legislation in force.
To maintain the market would require EUR 16-18 million per year".
The case of Bologna deserves special attention. It is the first Italian city to decide, in its concern over the closures, to remedy the problem through an agreement between the municipality and Anec in order to protect and boost single-room cinemas in both the city and downtown.
The provisions would include tax incentives for operators and benefits for the public to facilitate accessibility: viewers can drive into restricted zones and park at preferential tariffs in certain parking lots.
"I like this initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities, even by introducing other measures, will follow Bologna's example.
However, it is also certain that traditional cinemas, in order to be able to fight the domination of multiplexes, need to improve sound and image quality, because today's audience is much more demanding.
The preservation of traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of Supercinema in Bagheria - where I spent my childhood and youth - gave me the spark that eventually made Cinema Paradiso, although I had been thinking about it for 10 years.
