The energy is coming from the waves, and now the big ones are coming.
An inexhaustible energy source that accounts for 70 percent of the planet's surface and is still being discovered by large international energy companies
Waves, sea currents, tides, all renewable energy sources that have been sighted by giants like Chevron, who are now trying to get their hands on it.
For a hundred years, they have been looking for ways to get energy from the motions of the sea. In the 1970s, during the first oil crisis, research has intensified.
Around 1980, when oil prices decreased, the idea of using marine energy was put aside, but today the demand for environmental protection and the rise in oil prices are giving the sector a new impetus.
The World Energy Council of London (WEC) estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity demand could be covered by facilities exploiting sea surges.
This quantity is twice what nuclear power plants are currently producing.
Besides that, there would still be currents and tides.
The giants are swinging.
Enersis was the first company to commit to marine energy and signed an agreement in 2005 on a power plant to be established in northern Portugal.
It seemed like a revolutionary move when the signature was announced.
Two years have passed since then, and more and more companies are voting for marine energy, including those who have been committed supporters of traditional energy so far.
"Chevron is studying technologies exploiting the energy of the oceans and is considering the possibility of cooperating with us," stated Wall Street Journal, a spokesperson for an associated venture of the American oil giant.
The cooperation in question concerns the acquisition of the licence required by the US Energy Commission to launch the offshore energy project in Alaska.
This is not of little importance, especially considering that the US is currently extracting oil in Alaska, and even President Bush has recently launched a plan for further drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. in New York City and Ocean Power in New Jersey are also on the road to extractable energy from the sea.
The technology is waiting to be developed.
According to experts, it is still a primitive technology, even because the energy from the sea does not dispel doubts about the environmental impact.
Existing facilities such as Portugal or Scotland are all small and therefore do not cause much problems with the ecosystem.
However, in order to produce more energy on a larger scale, we need facilities with a more significant environmental impact.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses a interconnected buoy system.
Pushes generated by the waves and moving buoys up and down are converted into hydraulic pressure by the pistons and cylinders placed in them.
The pressure turns a turbine, which feeds a generator.
Electricity travels to land on cables under the sea.
For the time being, there are four similar facilities in the planning phase, which are waiting for federal approval, some of the energy produced would be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started power generation for a shopping mall and a parking lot with the help of six underwater turbines located in the East River Strait in New York City.
At tide, the movement of water turns the blades of turbines, and this rotating movement feeds the generator.
Verdant said that it has a long list of partners who are just waiting for permits to use energy.
It's tidal after waves.
At present, there is a need for particular attention to be paid to the opportunities that can be exploited by tides.
Although it is a periodic phenomenon, tidal tides are more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and can therefore be considered a more reliable energy source.
New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as the other coastal states, spent $7.5 million in 2008, just to exploit the energy supplied by tides, which is projected to increase to $35 million in 2009.
